image.altText: A group of Matildas footballers jump together in delight, celebrating a big win at the Women's World Cup.

items.synopsis: The Matildas beat France 7-6 in a dramatic sudden-death penalty shootout in Brisbane, with Mackenzie Arnold and Courtnee Vine the heroes. Follow all the updates in our live blog.

title.children: Matildas beat France in sudden death penalty shootout to reach Women's World Cup semifinal

liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: Cortnee Vine has the moment, firing in the decisive penalty, but that whole shootout is Mackenzie Arnold's moment. She was absolutely immense and kept the Matildas in it time and time and time again. And this team, after getting the advantage and then falling behind, to hold their nerve every time and just keep firing them in under all the pressure. What a frankly ridiculous performance in a match that will go down as one of the finest moments in Australian sporting folklore. Yeah. The. GIRLS!!!
liveBlogPostPrepared.title: THE MATILDAS HAVE DONE IT!! THEY'RE THROUGH ON PENALTIES!!!

children.content: Cortnee Vine has the moment, firing in the decisive penalty, but that whole shootout is Mackenzie Arnold's moment.
She was absolutely immense and kept the Matildas in it time and time and time again.

And this team, after getting the advantage and then falling behind, to hold their nerve every time and just keep firing them in under all the pressure. What a frankly ridiculous performance in a match that will go down as one of the finest moments in Australian sporting folklore.

liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: This is probably the best likely outcome for the Matildas after that extra time period where they looked pretty outgunned and outworked, but this is still pretty hectic. Opposing coaches Tony Gustavsson and Herve Renard shared a laugh and dapped each other up BEFORE that last corner went in, but things are decidedly more tense now as both teams sort their orders and tactics. Spare a though for the French keepers. Pauline Peyraud-Magnin had a good game but now misses out on potential glory, while Solene Durand has to come in cold and do the hardest job a goalkeeper can.
liveBlogPostPrepared.title: IT'S TIME FOR A PENALTY SHOOTOUT!!

children.content: This is probably the best likely outcome for the Matildas after that extra time period where they looked pretty outgunned and outworked, but this is still pretty hectic.

Opposing coaches Tony Gustavsson and Herve Renard shared a laugh and dapped each other up BEFORE that last corner went in, but things are decidedly more tense now as both teams sort their orders and tactics.
Spare a though for the French keepers. Pauline Peyraud-Magnin had a good game but now misses out on potential glory, while Solene Durand has to come in cold and do the hardest job a goalkeeper can.

liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: Vicki Becho and Dali Kenza combined well to end the first half of extra time, but Mackenzie Arnold came to Australia's rescue. Just. It does feel like the Matildas are holding on. Even the chances they've created have been pretty haphazard rather than some masterful plan. But it's still 0-0. They're still creating those chances. Penalties?
liveBlogPostPrepared.title: One period of extra time down. It's still 0-0!

children.content: Vicki Becho and Dali Kenza combined well to end the first half of extra time, but Mackenzie Arnold came to Australia's rescue. Just.
